ACT Ι. SCENE 2.--VERSES 85-156.

(1) Cinium-rans Anu Svnorsm—-In this scene Tranio's young master is brought upon the stage. In scene 1 Grumio had given a general expose of his young master’s ribald conduct, visiting the chief blame therefor on the seductions of Tranio. Now, not unlike another Prodigal Son, Philolaches himself, in a penitent but maudlin state of mind, comes forward and delivers himself of a parable os a house. The house had been well built and neatly adorned, but neglectful tenants had let it go to rack and ruin from exposure to rain and wind. So he, Philolaches, had been well reared, but, when he become tenant of his own soul, had proved neglectful ; love and desire had come like wind and rain, and brought to ruin the tabernacle of his soul.
